      <div class="bottom-L-window style-7 smr">
        <div>
          <h4> SMR Pressure-Point Massage</h4>
        </div>
        <div class="smr-card">
          <img class="trapezius" src="images/neck/upper-trap-acupressure.jpg">
          <p class="card-title"> Upper Trapezius Self-Massage </p>
          <p class="directions"> Requires : Tennis/Lacrosse ball or Theracane Device </p>
          <p class="directions"> Lastly, feel for the area where the trapezius anchors right by the shoulder joint (Gb.21). </p>
          <img src="images/smr/trapezius-massage-with-massage-ball.jpg">
          <p class="directions"> Apply pressure by leaning against a wall with the ball in position over the trigger point. Roll out any areas of tension between this point, in towards the base of your neck (Si.15).</p>
          <img src="images/shoulders/upper-traps-trigger-points.jpg">
        </div>
        <div class="smr-card">
          <img src="images/neck/Levator-Scapulae-muscle.png">
          {{!-- https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5QiUzWE9Z7M --}}
          <p class="card-title"> Levator Scapulae Self-Massage </p>
          <p class="directions"> Requires : Tennis/Lacrosse ball or Theracane Device </p>
          {{!-- <p class="directions"> Apply and hold pressure to the pair of points (Gb-20) <i>centrally-located between your ear and base of your skull</i> (you will feel a small bump in the bone where the muscle attaches). 
             You can use a device, the thumbs, or the pointer/middle fingers.</p> --}}
          <p class="directions"> Feel for tension in the points at the base of the neck, just above the shoulder blade (Si.15). </p>
          <img src="images/smr/levator-scapulae-massageball.jpg">
          <p class="directions"> Apply pressure by leaning against a wall with the ball in position over the trigger point. Roll out any areas of tension between this point, up to the base of your skull (Gb.20).</p>
          <img src="images/smr/SMR Trapezius-Upper.png">
        </div>
        <div class="smr-card">
          {{!-- <img src="images/neck/Sternocleidomastoid-trigger-points.jpg"> --}}
          <img src="images/neck/sternomastoid-points.png">
          <p class="card-title"> Sternomastoid Self-Massage </p>
          <p class="directions"> Turn your head to the left to expose the Right-side SCM. With your lefthand, grab the muscle between your thumb and pointer - starting at it's lowest point just above the collarbone.</p> 
          <p class="directions"> Make sure you squeeze the muscle between the thumb and finger. Do NOT press into the neck with the tips of the digits, taking care that you don't mistakenly compress the carotid artery as you move furter up the muscle (as this would make you feel lightheaded). </p>
          <p class="directions"> Gently test for tender spots as you work your way up the muscle towards it's "head", which attaches just behind the ear. Wherever you feel a tender point, squeeze down on the muscle and tilt the head back, hold it for a few seconds, and then (while still squeezing) turn your head to the right.</p>
          <p class="directions"> Repeat the above steps for the Left-side SCM, turning your head to the right to expose the muscle, squeezing it, then tilting the head back and then to the left. </p>
          <img src="images/smr/SCM-pinch-release.jpg">
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bottom-R-window style-7 stretch">
        <div>
          <h4> Follow-up Stretches </h4>
        </div>
        <div class="stretch-card">
          <img src="images/neck/trapezius-side-stretch.jpg">
          <p class="card-title"> Trapezius Side Stretch </p>
          <p class="directions"> Tilt your head horizontally to the side, resting your hand on the top-side of your head. Push your head up into your hand, while using your arm to gently resist. </p>
          <p class="directions"> After holding this for as long as you can, release and allow yourself to sink deeper into the stretch. </p>
          <p class="directions"> Repeat for the other side. If tension is more on one side, make sure to stretch that side more thoroughly. </p> 
        </div>
        <div class="stretch-card">
          <img src="images/neck/down-diag-neck-stretch.jpg">
          <p class="card-title"> Levator Scapulae Stretch </p>
          <p class="directions"> Tilt head diagonally downward, resting your hand on the back of your head. Push your head up into your hand, while using your arm to gently resist. </p>
          <p class="directions"> After holding this for as long as you can, release and allow yourself to sink deeper into the stretch. </p>
          <p class="directions"> Repeat for the other side. If tension is more on one side, make sure to stretch that side more thoroughly. </p> 
          <img src="images/neck/levator_scapulae_ani.gif">
        </div>
        <div class="stretch-card">
          <img src="images/neck/sternocleidomastoid-side-stretch.jpg">
          <p class="card-title"> Sternomastoid Stretch </p>
          <p class="directions"> Tilt head diagonally upward, resting your hand across your forehead. Push your head up into your hand, while using your arm to gently resist. </p>
          <p class="directions"> After holding this for as long as you can, release and allow yourself to sink deeper into the stretch. </p> 
          <p class="directions"> Repeat for the other side. If tension is more on one side, make sure to stretch the side more thoroughly. </p>  
          <img src="images/neck/sternomastoid-ani.gif">
        </div>

      </div>
